<h2>Bioinformatics & Systems Biology: Integrative Tools for Therapeutic Innovation</h2>

  <div class="section">
    <h2>1. Bioinformatics</h2>
    <p>Bioinformatics is the science of collecting, analyzing, and interpreting biological data—especially large-scale datasets from genomics, proteomics, and structural biology.</p>
    <h3>Core Functions</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Sequence analysis and motif discovery</li>
      <li>Protein modeling and docking</li>
      <li>Omics data integration</li>
      <li>Machine learning for prediction and annotation</li>
    </ul>
    <h3>Key Tools & Techniques</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>BLAST, Clustal Omega – sequence alignment</li>
      <li>AlphaFold, Rosetta – structure prediction</li>
      <li>Bioconductor, Galaxy – omics pipelines</li>
      <li>Databases: NCBI, UniProt, PDB, TCGA, STRING</li>
    </ul>
    <h3>Applications</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Variant interpretation in precision medicine</li>
      <li>Structure-based drug design</li>
      <li>Functional annotation of novel genes</li>
      <li>Biomarker discovery and patient stratification</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2>2. Systems Biology</h2>
    <p>Systems Biology focuses on understanding biological systems as dynamic, interconnected networks—moving beyond reductionist views to holistic modeling.</p>
    <h3>Core Concepts</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Network biology and regulatory interactions</li>
      <li>Dynamic modeling using ODEs and Boolean logic</li>
      <li>Multi-scale integration from molecules to tissues</li>
      <li>Feedback loops and emergent behaviors</li>
    </ul>
    <h3>Key Tools & Platforms</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Cytoscape – network visualization</li>
      <li>CellDesigner, COPASI – pathway simulation</li>
      <li>SBML, BioPAX – model exchange standards</li>
      <li>Omics integration: iCluster, MOFA, NetICS</li>
    </ul>
    <h3>Applications</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Predicting drug response and resistance</li>
      <li>Identifying regulatory hubs for targeting</li>
      <li>Modeling disease progression</li>
      <li>Designing synthetic biology circuits</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2>3. Comparative Overview</h2>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Feature</th>
          <th>Bioinformatics</th>
          <th>Systems Biology</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Focus</td>
          <td>Data analysis and interpretation</td>
          <td>Network modeling and simulation</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Scale</td>
          <td>Molecular (genes, proteins)</td>
          <td>Multi-level (molecules to systems)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Tools</td>
          <td>Sequence alignment, structure prediction</td>
          <td>Network visualization, dynamic modeling</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Output</td>
          <td>Annotated datasets, predictions</td>
          <td>Mechanistic models, emergent behaviors</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Role in Drug Discovery</td>
          <td>Target identification, structure-based design</td>
          <td>Pathway analysis, combination therapy design</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2>4. Strategic Integration in Therapeutics</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Target Prioritization:</strong> Bioinformatics identifies candidates; systems biology ranks them by network impact.</li>
      <li><strong>Mechanism of Action:</strong> Systems biology models perturbation; bioinformatics validates molecular changes.</li>
      <li><strong>Precision Medicine:</strong> Bioinformatics stratifies patients; systems biology predicts individualized responses.</li>
      <li><strong>AI Integration:</strong> Machine learning enhances both fields—predicting interactions and optimizing models.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>


